description:
Purpose: Define and implement Tauri IPC commands for Svelte frontend.

Background:
Tauri provides #[tauri::command] macros to expose Rust functions to the frontend. We need commands for:
- Daemon lifecycle (start, stop, restart)
- RPC passthrough (forward JSON-RPC to daemon)
- Settings management (get, set, persist)
- Diagnostics (export bundle)

Commands to Implement:
#[tauri::command]
async fn daemon_start(app: AppHandle) -> Result<(), String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn daemon_stop(app: AppHandle) -> Result<(), String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn daemon_health(app: AppHandle) -> Result<HealthResponse, String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn rpc_call(app: AppHandle, method: String, params: Value) -> Result<Value, String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn get_settings(app: AppHandle) -> Result<AppSettings, String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn set_settings(app: AppHandle, settings: AppSettings) -> Result<(), String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn export_diagnostics(app: AppHandle, path: String) -> Result<(), String>;

#[tauri::command]
async fn get_attach_command(app: AppHandle, pane_id: String) -> Result<String, String>;

Frontend Usage:
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api/core';
const health = await invoke('daemon_health');
const result = await invoke('rpc_call', { method: 'sessions.list', params: {} });

Acceptance Criteria:
- [ ] All commands implemented
- [ ] Error handling works
- [ ] TypeScript types generated
- [ ] Frontend can call all commands

Files: app/src-tauri/src/commands.rs, app/src/lib/tauri.ts

Purpose: Set up Svelte 5 stores and state management for dashboard.

Background:
Svelte 5 introduces runes for reactive state. We need stores for:
- Sessions and panes
- Events (compacts, escalations)
- Stats (hourly, daily)
- Connection state
- Settings

Store Structure:
// sessions.svelte.ts
export const sessions = $state<Session[]>([]);
export const selectedSession = $state<string | null>(null);

// events.svelte.ts
export const events = $state<Event[]>([]);
export const lastEventId = $state<number>(0);

// stats.svelte.ts
export const hourlyStats = $state<HourlyStats[]>([]);
export const dailyStats = $state<DailyStats[]>([]);

// connection.svelte.ts
export const connectionState = $state<ConnectionState>('disconnected');
export const lastHealthCheck = $state<Date | null>(null);

Data Flow:
1. Daemon sends notification
2. Tauri IPC to frontend
3. Store updated
4. Components re-render

Tauri IPC:
- listen() for daemon events
- invoke() for RPC calls
- Use typed events with TypeScript

Acceptance Criteria:
- [ ] Session store works
- [ ] Event store works
- [ ] Connection state reflects reality
- [ ] Components react to changes

Files: app/src/lib/stores/

Purpose: Add retry logic for transient API failures.

Background:
Network glitches and daemon hiccups cause transient failures. Automatic retry improves reliability.

Retry Strategy:
- Idempotent requests: Retry up to 3 times
- Non-idempotent requests: No auto-retry, surface error
- Backoff: 100ms, 200ms, 400ms

Idempotent Methods:
- health.get
- sessions.list, sessions.get
- panes.get
- events.list
- stats.*
- config.get

Non-Idempotent Methods:
- escalations.dismiss
- actions.sessionKill
- actions.paneSend
- config.set

Implementation:
async function rpcWithRetry(method, params, options) {
  for (let attempt = 0; attempt < options.maxRetries; attempt++) {
    try {
      return await rpc(method, params);
    } catch (error) {
      if (!isRetryable(error) || attempt === options.maxRetries - 1) {
        throw error;
      }
      await sleep(options.backoff[attempt]);
    }
  }
}

Error Classification:
- Retryable: timeout, connection reset, 503
- Not retryable: 400, 401, 404, business errors

Acceptance Criteria:
- [ ] Retry logic implemented
- [ ] Correct classification
- [ ] Backoff working
- [ ] Non-idempotent excluded

Files: app/src/lib/daemon/rpc.ts
